He arrived in England, beat the Anglo Saxons and crowned

00:03:40.061 --> 00:03:44.461
himself king of England on Christmas Day in 1066.

00:03:45.851 --> 00:03:52.291
He implemented a wide range of changes to the country, but the most important for the

00:03:52.291 --> 00:03:58.141
purposes of this episode was the introduction of something called the feudal system.

00:03:59.681 --> 00:04:05.081
Previously, England was administered by a group of Anglo-Saxon nobles.

00:04:05.931 --> 00:04:09.581
When William arrived, he took all of this land.

00:04:10.691 --> 00:04:17.281
Just under 20% he kept for himself, and the rest was distributed between a

00:04:17.301 --> 00:04:23.411
combination of the church and men who had been given noble titles by King William.

00:04:24.631 --> 00:04:29.481
In practice, the deal was this: the king would give a nobleman

00:04:29.681 --> 00:04:33.564
a chunk of land, often thousands of square kilometres.

00:04:34.321 --> 00:04:40.071
The nobleman would be in charge of everything and everyone who lived there: he

00:04:40.071 --> 00:04:45.381
could do what he wanted, collect taxes, collect rent, he was the boss, essentially.

00:04:46.711 --> 00:04:52.992
In exchange, he needed to pay a small annual fee to the crown, give advice to the king if

00:04:53.052 --> 00:05:00.172
asked, and if the king needed soldiers to fight a war, the nobleman would provide them for him.

00:05:01.252 --> 00:05:06.172
It was, for the king and the nobleman at least, a pretty efficient arrangement.

00:05:07.062 --> 00:05:11.302
The king didn’t need to worry about minor things going on hundreds

00:05:11.302 --> 00:05:14.402
of kilometres away because someone else would deal with it.

00:05:15.272 --> 00:05:21.902
And the nobleman, well, he got to live a pretty good life and was under the protection of the king.

00:05:23.292 --> 00:05:28.792
For everyone else, well, life wasn’t quite so rosy, but that isn’t what we’re talking about today.

00:05:30.202 --> 00:05:37.742
The catch-all term for these noblemen was “the baronage”, and it consisted of no more than a

00:05:37.742 --> 00:05:45.332
couple of hundred “barons”, of whom never more than 25 were bestowed with the title “Earl”.

00:05:46.872 --> 00:05:53.412
As the years went by, more titles were created: Duke, Marquess, and Viscount.

00:05:54.872 --> 00:06:00.492
Initially these titles weren’t actually hereditary: the son of an

00:06:00.492 --> 00:06:04.762
Earl didn’t automatically become an Earl after his father died.

00:06:05.702 --> 00:06:10.172
But within a couple of hundred years, and after a few changes

00:06:10.172 --> 00:06:13.582
that we aren’t going to go into today, this became the case.

00:06:14.212 --> 00:06:19.792
If a man was a baron, let’s say, after his death the title would pass to his son.

00:06:20.722 --> 00:06:23.532
If he didn’t have any children, it went to his brother.

00:06:24.202 --> 00:06:27.302
If he had a daughter, well, her husband would get it.

00:06:28.022 --> 00:06:34.212
Sorry, women couldn’t be trusted to take on the title, it would have to go to the nearest man.

00:06:35.676 --> 00:06:44.066
And, with a few minor updates, this is essentially still the situation today: there are

00:06:44.066 --> 00:06:49.796
these different noble titles which pass from father to son and give the holder of the

00:06:49.806 --> 00:06:58.667
title the same land and power that can in many cases be traced all the way back to 1066.

00:06:59.926 --> 00:07:05.686
Before we go into what this means in practice in the 21st century, let me first

00:07:05.686 --> 00:07:11.016
explain to you the hierarchy of these noble titles, their order of importance,

00:07:11.546 --> 00:07:16.526
so if you ever find yourself in a room with a Duke, a Marquess, an Earl,

00:07:16.736 --> 00:07:20.766
a Viscount and a Baron, you’ll know in which order you need to greet them.

00:07:22.026 --> 00:07:28.226
In fact, the order I just gave you is the right order, going from highest in rank to lowest.

00:07:29.386 --> 00:07:33.636
Right at the top is “Duke”, of which there are only 30.

00:07:34.506 --> 00:07:39.172
These include Dukes you have probably heard of, like the Duke of Cornwall,

00:07:39.526 --> 00:07:43.586
otherwise known as Prince William, the Duke of Sussex, which is Prince

00:07:43.586 --> 00:07:49.226
Harry, or their black sheep of an uncle, Prince Andrew, the Duke of York.

00:07:50.796 --> 00:07:56.966
If you know your English geography, Cornwall, Sussex and York are all areas

00:07:56.976 --> 00:08:02.936
of the country, so being a Duke of a particular area typically meant that

00:08:02.946 --> 00:08:07.596
the title came with ownership and management of that area of the country.

00:08:08.656 --> 00:08:12.976
Now, in fact in the case of Sussex and York, these titles were created

00:08:12.976 --> 00:08:18.687
more recently specifically for that person, but the Duke of Cornwall

00:08:18.895 --> 00:08:23.346
is a title that can be traced all the way back to the year 1337.

00:08:24.856 --> 00:08:29.966
One step down from a “Duke” is a Marquess, of which there are 34.

00:08:30.726 --> 00:08:34.096
Then comes Earl, of which there are 189.

00:08:34.936 --> 00:08:40.566
There are fewer Viscounts, only 110, but they are still less important than Earls.

00:08:41.386 --> 00:08:45.076
And Barons are, comparatively, two a penny.

00:08:45.376 --> 00:08:49.056
There are 426 hereditary barons in England.

00:08:50.396 --> 00:08:58.226
If you’ve been doing the maths, that’s 789 people, it’s 0.001% of the population.

00:09:00.206 --> 00:09:05.426
Given this, and given the fact that these people don't live “normal”

00:09:05.426 --> 00:09:09.786
lives by most people’s definitions, you are unlikely to meet one.

00:09:10.626 --> 00:09:14.476
But if you did, let me tell you how to address that person.

00:09:15.666 --> 00:09:16.966
It’s actually quite simple.

00:09:17.286 --> 00:09:21.736
If you are addressing one of the 30 Dukes, you say “Your Grace”.

00:09:22.176 --> 00:09:25.876
Unless, that is, that Duke is also a prince or

00:09:25.876 --> 00:09:29.276
princess, in which you would say “Your Royal Highness”.

00:09:30.726 --> 00:09:37.786
And for everyone else, all of the other titles, it is “Lord” for a man, and “Lady” for a lady.

00:09:38.556 --> 00:09:45.576
So a “lord” is actually just the way in which you address someone, it isn’t a rank in its own right.

00:09:47.166 --> 00:09:52.293
Right, now that we have an understanding of the order of these titles, and

00:09:52.373 --> 00:09:56.643
what we should call people who hold them, it’s time to talk about the role of

00:09:56.643 --> 00:10:02.426
these nobles, and ask ourselves what their purpose is in 21st century Britain.

00:10:03.886 --> 00:10:08.946
If you remember, the original role of these people was a practical one:

00:10:09.636 --> 00:10:15.256
control the land, advise the king, bring soldiers to fight when the king asks.

00:10:16.736 --> 00:10:21.086
The UK now has a functional government, the monarch is no longer really

00:10:21.086 --> 00:10:25.636
in charge, and fortunately there is limited  need for a large army.

00:10:26.247 --> 00:10:31.083
So, what is the purpose of the nobility in 2023?

00:10:32.227 --> 00:10:39.097
Well, for some people this is a very easy question to answer: there is no purpose at all, there

00:10:39.217 --> 00:10:44.487
hasn’t been any purpose for hundreds of years, and we should dissolve all of these ridiculous

00:10:44.497 --> 00:10:50.937
titles and return the land owned by the 0.001% of the population to the British people.

00:10:52.527 --> 00:10:59.417
To others, the role of the British nobility is similar to that of the monarchy: it is one of

00:10:59.637 --> 00:11:06.277
historical and cultural preservation and continuity, they are a living link to British history.

00:11:07.757 --> 00:11:13.057
We’ll engage with this question a little more in a bit, but your next question might

00:11:13.057 --> 00:11:19.437
be about what Dukes or Earls or Viscounts have to do…do they have to do anything

00:11:19.437 --> 00:11:24.417
now, or do they just sit around getting frustrated with having to scroll all the way

00:11:24.417 --> 00:11:28.277
down to the bottom when it comes to filling out the form for a doctor’s appointment?

00:11:29.477 --> 00:11:35.817
Well, there are some ceremonial and symbolic responsibilities, such as

00:11:35.977 --> 00:11:41.097
going to events, weddings, banquets, opening new buildings and so on.

00:11:41.687 --> 00:11:48.347
But other than this, there is little “official” work required, you don’t need to do anything.

00:11:49.767 --> 00:11:55.417
Other than the status that might come from having this kind of title, and the invitations

00:11:55.417 --> 00:12:02.127
to fancy parties and events, you now don’t get anything directly from being a lord or lady.

00:12:02.817 --> 00:12:06.917
In fact, it is normally a pretty expensive title to hold.

00:12:07.987 --> 00:12:13.917
This kind of title will often come with a very large house that is in varying states of

00:12:13.917 --> 00:12:19.597
disrepair, so it needs substantial money put into it every year to stop it from falling down.

00:12:20.517 --> 00:12:24.777
Your family in most cases will still have a very healthy bank

00:12:24.797 --> 00:12:28.717
balance, but there are certain standards that are expected to be

00:12:28.717 --> 00:12:33.907
maintained, and the money probably goes out as quickly as it comes in.

00:12:35.027 --> 00:12:39.777
After all, this is no longer the 14th century, and there aren’t hundreds of

00:12:39.777 --> 00:12:43.927
thousands of commoners farming your land and paying you rent every month.

00:12:45.447 --> 00:12:50.537
In some cases, however, not that much has changed since the 14th century.

00:12:51.547 --> 00:12:56.357
