00:12:57.507 --> 00:13:01.127
He is only 32 years old as of the time of making this

00:13:01.127 --> 00:13:06.195
episode, and he is worth a staggering €11 billion.

00:13:07.527 --> 00:13:13.457
He does, much like his father and grandfather and their grandfathers before them, sit

00:13:13.497 --> 00:13:19.797
around and collect rent, not from farmers, but from companies and private individuals.

00:13:21.247 --> 00:13:26.507
In his case, this wealth comes from owning just over a kilometre squared

00:13:26.537 --> 00:13:31.397
of property in the fanciest areas of London, Mayfair and Belgravia.

00:13:33.041 --> 00:13:38.487
And his title, the Duke of Westminster, can be traced back hundreds of years.

00:13:39.337 --> 00:13:45.617
Indeed, his father apparently once joked to a group of entrepreneurs that his top piece

00:13:45.617 --> 00:13:51.177
of advice was “to have an ancestor who was good friends with William the Conqueror”.

00:13:52.697 --> 00:13:59.537
And in just one more example of not that much changing, this Duke of Westminster, Hugh,

00:14:00.037 --> 00:14:07.147
had two older sisters, yet the title and wealth passed to him, not his older sisters.

00:14:08.777 --> 00:14:12.927
Now, there is one type of Lord that we haven’t talked about yet.

00:14:13.917 --> 00:14:19.157
Up until now we have talked only about hereditary titles, Duke, Earl,

00:14:19.487 --> 00:14:24.767
Viscount and so on, titles that pass from one generation to the next.

00:14:26.427 --> 00:14:31.087
There is another type of Lord which doesn’t pass down, and that is called

00:14:31.107 --> 00:14:36.147
a “Life Peerage”, and if you have a “Life Peerage” you are called a “peer”.

00:14:37.527 --> 00:14:41.277
If you have read much about the British political system, you’ll know that

00:14:41.287 --> 00:14:46.887
the UK Parliament is formed of the House of Commons and the House of Lords.

00:14:48.127 --> 00:14:54.387
A commoner is someone without a title, a normal person, and the House of Commons is

00:14:54.387 --> 00:15:00.437
the area of Parliament where elected officials sit and discuss political matters.

00:15:01.247 --> 00:15:05.297
If you’ve seen videos of a long room with green seats and people

00:15:05.307 --> 00:15:08.627
standing up and shouting at each other, that’s the House of Commons.

00:15:09.737 --> 00:15:13.227
But in the same building there is another room.

00:15:13.837 --> 00:15:17.457
It’s a bit smaller, and the seats are red, not green.

00:15:18.117 --> 00:15:22.957
It’s called The House of Lords, and you have to be a Lord to enter.

00:15:24.107 --> 00:15:29.737
It used to be made up of hereditary peers, Lords and Ladies who inherited

00:15:29.737 --> 00:15:36.147
their titles from their parents, but the law was changed in 1999 so that, with

00:15:36.187 --> 00:15:41.117
a small number of exceptions, you now have to be “elected” as a Lord or Lady.

00:15:42.247 --> 00:15:48.677
The election process, however, is not exactly democratic; typically the Prime

00:15:48.677 --> 00:15:53.537
Minister will propose someone because of a particular contribution that they

00:15:53.537 --> 00:15:59.217
have made to the world of politics, arts, science, business or public service.

00:16:00.187 --> 00:16:05.357
And recently, several Prime Ministers, especially Boris Johnson, have

00:16:05.367 --> 00:16:10.447
come under fire for rewarding people loyal to them with life peerages

00:16:10.807 --> 00:16:14.887
despite their somewhat dubious contribution to British society.

00:16:16.077 --> 00:16:21.767
And when you become a life peer, you are a peer for life, forever.

00:16:22.447 --> 00:16:27.627
You can put “The Right Honourable” before your name, you can come and vote on issues in the House

00:16:27.627 --> 00:16:33.627
of Lords, you get paid for your contribution, you have a political role to play in the country.

00:16:34.527 --> 00:16:38.907
Now, this wasn’t meant to be an episode on how the British political system

00:16:38.907 --> 00:16:45.717
works, but broadly the role of these peers, and the House of Lords, is to

00:16:45.717 --> 00:16:50.977
“make laws, investigate public policy, and hold the government to account.”

00:16:52.687 --> 00:16:57.967
If you are familiar with US politics, it’s somewhat similar to the Senate,

00:16:58.387 --> 00:17:01.747
while the House of Commons is more like the House of Representatives.

00:17:02.607 --> 00:17:06.617
There are fundamental differences, like the fact that members of the House of

00:17:06.617 --> 00:17:12.787
Lords are not elected by the public, but we are in the UK after all, and as you’ll

00:17:12.787 --> 00:17:17.677
have gathered by now, we have a long-standing tradition of unelected rulers.

00:17:18.587 --> 00:17:24.947
Now, the final point I want to talk to you about today is the public perception of nobility.

00:17:26.337 --> 00:17:30.807
On one level, it is clearly ridiculous to give people titles

00:17:31.057 --> 00:17:34.627
based on who their ancestors might have been in the 14th century.

00:17:35.427 --> 00:17:40.667
If you were designing a society from scratch, it seems unlikely that you would give a

00:17:40.677 --> 00:17:46.457
large proportion of the country’s land to a tiny slither of the population and allow

00:17:46.467 --> 00:17:52.392
that miniscule group of people to continue to call themselves Duke or Earl or Marquess.

00:17:53.097 --> 00:17:57.697
But on the other hand, both inside and outside of Britain,

00:17:58.207 --> 00:18:02.427
there is a strange obsession with this tiny section of society.

00:18:03.257 --> 00:18:08.427
If you think of the books, films, and TV series that have been made about Lords and

00:18:08.427 --> 00:18:14.787
Ladies, from Downton Abbey to Gosford Park, Poldark to Brideshead Revisited, people

00:18:14.827 --> 00:18:21.107
love reading about, watching and experiencing the lives that the aristocracy lead.

00:18:21.577 --> 00:18:23.967
This genre is incredibly popular.

00:18:25.307 --> 00:18:32.407
And if we were to look into a crystal ball and think, hmm, will the British aristocracy be

00:18:32.407 --> 00:18:39.671
any different in 500 or even 1,000 years to come, well this is an interesting question indeed.

00:18:40.811 --> 00:18:46.241
There have been some reforms to this system, but really there is

00:18:46.241 --> 00:18:50.841
very little public support or movement at the moment for any kind of

00:18:50.841 --> 00:18:56.281
dismantling of the system of peerage, of Dukes, Earls, Barons and so on.

00:18:57.551 --> 00:19:02.681
For most people, it is something that doesn’t touch on their life at all, and

00:19:02.951 --> 00:19:08.761
if anything, is a curiosity and interesting thing to read about or watch on TV.

00:19:10.301 --> 00:19:15.971
And at the end of the day, the title passes from parent to child, in many

00:19:15.971 --> 00:19:20.891
cases in such a clever way that no inheritance tax is ever paid on it.

00:19:21.851 --> 00:19:27.661
So, for as long as Dukes and Earls keep on having lots of children, and their money

00:19:27.661 --> 00:19:32.701
pots continue to pass from one generation to the next without the taxman getting

00:19:32.701 --> 00:19:37.941
a look inside, there will be more little Lords or Ladies for many years to come.

